Barack Obama becomes fourth US president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
American President Barack Obama arrives in Oslo, Norway, for 26 hours to become the fourth US president in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
He will also receive the diploma, medal and cheque for $1.4 million for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The White House chief of staff arrives in the Norwegian capital tomorrow with his wife Michelle and will be busy all the time.
First of all, he will visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with the five members of the committee who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organisations.
The presidential couple then scheduled a meeting with Norway's King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will culminate in the afternoon with the ceremony at which Obama will accept the prestigious award.
He is the fourth US president to receive the award, but only the third to receive it directly in office.
The White House has already indicated that Obama will speak about the Afghan war when accepting the award.
The President does not want to dodge this issue, because he knows that he is taking the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
He stepped up the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gold medal, diploma and cheque for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money to charity, but has not yet decided on a specific charitable work.
The programme will include a banquet with the President and his wife, attended not only by Norway's King and Queen, but also by the Prime Minister and 250 other invited guests.
Obama has been very reticent about the price from the start.
He said, for example, that he felt he didn't quite deserve the award.
He also repeated several times that this is a prize not only for him, but for all those who aspire to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he said it was a "call to action" for him.
