USA: Repetition is Mother of Wisdom
It is almost comical that Barack Obama, the president with his reputation for being the brightest, is repeating the strategy of his predecessor on Afghanistan, whom he himself considered the stupidest.
When he finally sweated out his long-awaited Afghanistan doctrine, it transpired that he copied it from the Bush-Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he even used the name of the Bush Declaration of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "New Way Forward," without hesitation.
Even three years ago, he criticized the Bush idea of sending fresh troop contingents to civil-war-ravaged Iraq as an "irresponsible and, in its aftermath, catastrophic decision."
The following months, however, showed that the Bush strategy, based on recommendations from the military, was the only possible one, and very successful to the extent that today there is no mention of Iraq at all in the news.
Bush's reputation has not been improved by this, for objectively he has left his successor with a much more grateful starting point than might have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama is hoping for a repeat of the miracle.
He has been asked again by the military to increase the troop contingent, especially by the commander-in-chief of the Afghanistan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, despite his habit of subordination, harshly criticized the dithering shooters in the White House.
He called for 40,000 troops to turn the situation around for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but did not come up with a better idea, so he cheated the general at least by 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe, he pressed for a further 5,000, even though he himself had originally expected at least 10,000.
What is most problematic about the whole Obama strategy is his plan to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and complete the process within three years. The whole Obama doctrine leaves more questions than answers.
Some doubt that the halved increase will have the same effect as the action in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal war of recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well structured, its leaders honoring values.
The Afghan situation is characterised by contraindication - no one can be relied on and no agreements are kept.
In these circumstances, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, who are used to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if they were formally founded correctly, remain only sham buildings behind which patriarchal ancestral relations will continue to proliferate.
The balance of interests between the different ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially because of the complexity of the situation, which further complicates Pakistan and Iran's influence.
Also, the building of an "effective state," which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, is very unrealistic.
Time horizon of Obama strategy bewildered by his voluntarism
Over the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and now it is on the verge of exploding.
Only a truly romantic soul who is unimpressed by facts can believe that the little soldiers who broke out into the howls of war about the "early return home" are able to create a miracle here.
From a political point of view, the date for troop withdrawal is pure irresponsibility, because the Taliban will take it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans' willingness to take part in the fighting in Afghanistan is coming to an end.
Nor can Europe's politicians explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy relates to the war in the Hindu Kush foothills.
Another possible factor that can radically influence the situation is the evolution of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not have an effect on the Iranians, the question for the United States is whether the problem cannot be solved with troops.
That question needs to be answered as America moves toward a post-Obama withdrawal from Afghanistan.
Any solution, however, will also mean a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is that there are still three years left until the presidential election, so there is plenty of time for him to resort to another strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
