Czech discovery: a substance that works even in 'hardened' HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not have as strong an effect on common virus variants as one of the existing drugs.
AIDS cannot yet be cured.
However, the combination of drugs can prolong the life of patients and prevent the replication of HIV viruses in the body.
However, your intake is accompanied by a whole range of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus replication also results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which no drugs are effective any more.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, the VSCHT (Chemical and Technological University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances known as metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the reproduction of the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus replication in a different way than all drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new 'improved' compounds, which have been prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multiple cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Treacherous and persistent virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV-virus cleavage caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would arise.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the replication of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in the press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work, which was published in the journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe entire series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically altered further.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against the HIV protease has been tested in the test tube, including against their stable (resistant) variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metalocarboranes on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as in the case of clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants, against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical compositions, make metalocarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, Head of the Structural Biology Laboratory of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
