According to the new timetable of CD (Czech Railways), fewer trains will run for approximately the same fare.
Czech Railways will terminate or restrict some low-capacity fast and local trains from 13 December, while other services will be strengthened.
From the date of validity of the new timetable, the total volume of traffic will be reduced by two percent compared to today.
Most fares including basic and customer fare will not be changed.
For example, residents of the Ostrava region will have several connections to the capital, and the railway will use Pendolino trains for this route.
The express train will no longer run to Bratislava.
Fewer fast trains will also operate on the Prague - Pisek - Budweis route, and direct connections from Prague to Letohrad will be reduced in principle.
The biggest reduction is planned by the railway in the district of Hradec Kralove, by a total of eight percent, whereas Prague and its surroundings can look forward to an increase.
Two overnight trains on the Prague - Tabor - Ceske Budejovice route will also be cancelled, and some fast trains on the Prague - Pisek - Ceske Budejovice route will be reduced to a few days a week.
One of the biggest changes is the introduction of a new direct route from Milovice to Prague, currently Milovice residents have to change to Lysa nad Labem.
It is the fifteenth transport route of the Esko suburban transport system, the opening of which is possible thanks to railway electrification from Lysa nad Labem to Milovice.
Long-distance routes to the capital will end at the destination station Prague - Main Railway Station.
The CD introduces more SC Pendolino lines between Prague and Ostrava and trains to Sumperk / Jesenik will run every two hours.
Passengers have not been able to travel to Bratislava on the Pendolino since 13 December.
