Vaccination against pneumococci free and voluntary
Vaccination against pneumococci changes from January.
It will be the first to be free and voluntary for families.
But already there are voices saying that mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of the free pneumococcal vaccine are culminating.
The Pharmaceutical Institute already sets the maximum prices of vaccines that health insurance companies have to pay.
Experts are also aware of the vaccination process.
New vaccination
Vaccines free for August kids
From January, children born on and after August 2 last year can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococcal infections.
The condition is that they have not yet received a vaccine dose.
Those who have already started with the vaccination in the last year or earlier must also pay for further repeated vaccination themselves.
The first dose of vaccination must be given between the 3rd and 5th month of the child's life.
Last year, a quarter of families had their children vaccinated against pneumococcal.
Parents paid 1600 kronor or more for a dose.
Four doses are required to vaccinate the youngest children.
In total, the experts estimate that health insurance companies spend 300,000 to 450,000 kroner per year on vaccination doses.
But they are saving on the treatment that children would need without vaccination.
So far, the state has spent about $500,000 a year on all of the children's vaccinations.
Mandatory vaccination was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococcal infections cause middle ear infections, but also serious infections including meningitis and blood poisoning.
Pneumococcal infections kill up to 28 children up to the age of 10 years per year, according to research carried out in hospitals.
Outside the Czech Republic, compulsory vaccination of children against pneumococcal disease has been introduced in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination may be compulsory in the future.
From January, this will be paid for by insurers and will be voluntary.
Rudolf Kalovsky, head of the Nahlas civic association, mentioned, for example, that mandatory vaccination would be better.
His association has long campaigned for the pneumococcal vaccine.
The experts at the international conference in which our association participated were not very satisfied with the fact that we have voluntary vaccination.
This is not ideal.
On the other hand, we are pleased that we have managed to achieve at least that.
"I think that's the path we have to take now," Kalovsky said.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination procedure.
"At this moment we are not considering it at all," said his spokesman, Vlastimil Sesen.
Voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors claim.
The President of the Society of Practical Pediatricians, Hana Cabrnochova, acknowledges that voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
If all children were vaccinated, one could think about reducing the number of repeat vaccinations. "In a situation where the vaccine is so expensive, we understand the political decision that this vaccination was started as a voluntary one," says Cabrnochova.
Experts expect more than 80 per cent of parents to have their babies vaccinated against pneumococcal from next year.
The pneumococcal vaccine is also groundbreaking in that it is the first to be paid for by health insurance companies, not the state.
Insurers should spend the money on prevention so they can save for further treatment, Cabrnochova said.
Doctors have to buy the vaccines themselves.
However, there is a concern among pediatricians about the purchase of the vaccines.
Under the original plan, the vaccines would be bought through insurance companies and doctors would receive them in the same way as other vaccines given to them by the state.
But some MPs worried that this would allow insurers to "take the money out of people's health insurance."
As a result, doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves and wait for insurance companies to pay for them.
According to estimates, individual general practitioners will have to invest 40 000 kronor per month, which is a significant sum.
"It's not going to be easy," Cabrnochova said.
