Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters have voted to ban the construction of minarets, and concern about the supposed Islamization of Europe is widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written an informed and considered report on whether Muslims can - and will - be integrated into one of Europe's avowedly secularized societies.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's latest work, "Why the French Don't Like Headscarves" (2006), an elegant and densely argued study of a contentious issue that divided and preoccupied the country for more than a decade and a half, the effects of which can still be seen today.
Bowen's latest book offers a broader and bolder range.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what the politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer what Bowen calls "Islamic freedom" to France's 5 to 6 million Muslims.
He is a good listener, reflecting debates between teachers and students on the issues that worry them most.
Should a Muslim get married in a mosque or town hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest-based banking system to obtain a mortgage?
It is these seemingly mundane matters, he claims, that make up daily life, in stark contrast to the political dramas that preoccupy the media.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers, and intellectuals, none of whom have a known name, with the possible exception of Tarik Ramadan, a Swiss-born Arab-Muslim scholar and academic.
This new generation is trying to open up the debate on how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen on the other in a modern secular society.
They don't have all the arguments on their side.
Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists Bowen surveyed are mostly at odds with their Salafi counterparts - advocates of purist Sunni Islam linked to Saudi Arabia - who now have a small but influential presence among Europe's Muslims.
Bowen believes Muslim values and French secularism can be reconciled.
But an agreement requires give and take on both sides.
It questions the extent to which French policymakers (and the intellectual elite that so passionately guards the separation of church and state) are truly committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may receive harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who in turn have had to make their historic compromise with secular republicanism.
He sees a "tightening of the screws on values" rather than a growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book, one is inclined to say "Yes, but not yet."
