The weak point, of course, as with other city school inspectors, is that they are trying to keep the white and black middle classes.
Our focus is to make sure we build a system of great schools.
We need to strengthen our neighbourhood schools so that all families, wherever they live, can be sure that their children can receive an excellent public education.
Janey, who is now a schools inspector in Newark, said in an interview this week that one of the most significant elements in closing the achievement gap is extending the traditional public school year, which is currently 180 days in Washington, to compete with charter schools.
