Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government officials have gradually softened their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city residents, members of ethnic minorities, and cases in which both husband and wife were only children -- and in 2007, the tone of many harsh slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Beijing University's Department of Population Research, said that government officials have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children with one partner as an only child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births in July.
Posters warning families to have only one child have been replaced almost overnight by guidelines detailing who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city government has sent city employees and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and push leaflets under the doors.
She also asked for psychological and financial counselling to be provided for those who have more than one child.
The reaction wasn't exactly encouraging, family planning officials said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a small rural town on the outskirts of Shanghai said there had been an uptick in applications from couples wanting a second child after the campaign was launched, urban districts reported no change.
Huinan Municipality, with a population of 115,000, still receives only four to five applications per month as an example.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the number of births expected in the city in 2010 will still be about 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Caolu Municipality Family Planning Committee in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have more children.
They want to give their best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would like to have two children and were legally allowed to do so.
But, like many Chinese, they have only minimal government health and life insurance.
Without a social safety net, they say, that decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misinterpret the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with her first child.
Yes, we are being deprived of the opportunity to have more than one child.
The problem, however, is not simply politics.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the human resources manager, said she only wanted one child because she was also an only child. "We were the center of the family and used to have everyone take care of us.
We're not used to looking after others and we don't really want to. '
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, put it more bluntly.
For middle-class parents with dual careers that are driving down the birth rate, he said, it's about being successful and being selfish.
The 20- to 39-year-olds today grew up watching their parents struggle during the early days of China's experiment in capitalism, and they don't want a life like that for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, imposes huge demands on parents "time.
A mother has to give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the space question -- "You have to remodel your home" -- and the life planning -- "When the child is 9 months old, you have to have a resume ready for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
"Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living," he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group Drafts Plan to Reduce Emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterized by wild posturing and recriminations -- refocused on Friday with the release of a document outlining an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with industrialized nations bearing the brunt of the burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, identified both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time as more than 100 world leaders arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, drafted by a specially created UN working group, makes no mention of the amount of money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how developed and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions, and what the upper limit for global temperature rise should be, which policymakers would support.
There will be a lot of flexibility in the process, said John Coequyt, a senior fellow at the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, has compiled a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, has called "the big picture."
It shows the outline of a possible agreement under which developed countries would collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also gave a boost to Friday's talks by pledging $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change, from coping with floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Friday, though, brought the same verbal fireworks that had dominated last week's talks.
Todd Stern, the US special envoy on climate change, has rejected language that calls for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared with voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if they are not financed by industrialized nations.
The move signaled that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China than Bush administration officials did less than two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement unless major emerging economies stand up and take action, said Stern, who also complained that the text did not go far enough to ensure that the cuts could be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern's comments came an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei said that America's top climate negotiator either lacked "common sense" or that it was "highly irresponsible" of him to say earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China tackle global warming.
With the future economic direction of the major world powers at stake, fault lines have opened up both within the industrialized nations, as well as between the industrialized and emerging economies.
The current struggle is as much about saving individual economies as it is about saving the planet, with China and the United States feuding over their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the major powers are fighting over who should bear the cost of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to be more aggressive in holding countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game of what will become a new economic hegemony, said Ulate, who also serves as a regional climate change adviser for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, though leaders say the talks will at best lead to a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States submitted a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the offensive by the small island states "exerts political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now united and are demanding action from emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues had to be resolved before the arrival of the leaders in order to reach an agreement.
Senior officials, such as India's Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China's Vice Minister, got off their planes and raced through the corridors of the Bella Center for closed-door meetings and press conferences to map out claims to be negotiated over the next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people go in and out of the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists put on nightly shows mocking the countries they believe are betraying and selling themselves, and draft contracts are passed from hand to hand rather than by e-mail -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is only just building: almost all the key ministers are here now, and from Wednesday, 60 government leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We're coming to the top of the league, "said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president of global policy for Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
Britain's first 225km / h train redefines the feel of Monday
A whistle will go through the darkness at 5.13am on Monday morning to announce a train journey that will revolutionise transport in Britain.
The first high-speed commuter train in the country will travel from Ashford, Kent, to London St Pancras at 225km / h, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
Dame Kelly Holmes will join Lord Adonis, the Transport Secretary, on board the first Javelin commuter service from London.
He hopes that the new service will eventually link the UK to an international network of fast, reliable trains, connecting the major metropolitan areas of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
The neglected province could become vibrant commuter cities, commute times would be radically reduced, and the switch from air and car to rail would reduce national carbon emissions and road congestion.
In theory, the three main parties believe in this vision.
But the many billions of pounds needed to build a new national rail network, the inevitable planning battle and fears of environmental damage could still put the brakes on Britain's high-speed railways.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to deliver a feasibility study to the Government, will hand the report to Lord Adonis on December 30, according to The Times.
This will provide him with a detailed route map of the next planned stage of the high-speed rail network.
The new rail line, which will link London to the West Midlands, will pass by urban areas and places where the impact on the environment is disputed, with a margin of five metres.
In open terrain, the plan will demonstrate the concept within 25 meters of the final route.
HS2 will also provide three options for a larger, northbound high-speed rail network.
Lord Adonis will respond in the spring.
The preferred option proposed is a Y-shaped route, where a single high-speed line would lead into the West Midlands.
The route would split in or near Birmingham, with one branch heading west of the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another heading north-east to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line would lead to Scotland.
"It seems to be the best option," said one rail insider.
Once completed, the journey time between London and Edinburgh would be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first leg, which would not open until 2025, would allow travellers to travel the London-Birmingham route in 49 minutes, compared to just over an hour today.
The proposals would allow trains to travel at speeds of 400km / h, making Britain's rail network the fastest in Europe.
The first line was planned in such a way that 400-metre-long trains with a maximum capacity of 1,100 people can travel on it.
Up to 18 trains an hour could be running on the London-Birmingham route.
This, in turn, would mean that a terminal would be needed in London, which could handle 20,000 travellers an hour.
Given the space constraints in the capital, an existing station is expected to be upgraded to accommodate the high-speed network.
Rail experts say only St Pancras International or Euston have this potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks the plan should go ahead, but the lengthy public consultation and planning process means a final decision will not be made until after the general election.
But even if it sets the wheels in motion, the rail network must be built in sections.
Trains would first have to switch from high-speed lines to existing lines in the north of Birmingham, which would still take more than three hours to travel between London and Scotland.
This is seen as a crucial sticking point in ensuring a switch from airplanes to railways, a benchmark for the rail revolution.
