Manager Revolution or the End of Strategic Early Reconnaissance?
If nothing changes in the leadership of large French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence has been in vain...
For over a decade, the attitude of management of large companies with respect to its employees, said the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: It is intended for staff to join "values" the best, as it used to impose on consumer products designed by the technicians in the factory.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution has given the strategies of conquering the markets in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products separately factors customer preferences again regularly!
A demobilisation of the employees can lead to a deadly demoralisation.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of a much larger phenomenon affecting employees in particular.
This demobilisation has a negative impact on the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, particularly those of R & D and, more importantly, those of economic intelligence.
Indeed, the IE (Intelligence Economique) demands "from all parties involved (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it demands from its staff a commitment that is completely contrary to the instructions of authoritarian management.
That is why we are calling for an operational revolution that would involve putting employees at the heart of the company's concerns on an equal footing with customers.
The very limited usefulness of internal opinion polls
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire Orange submitted to its wage earners, inspire this revolution in management practice?
Unfortunately, I fear not.
- Firstly, because I was able to see that, faced with a new situation, after many detours, the whole fabric is finally beginning to do what it has always done... as a matter of priority.
Also because authoritarianism - one of the pathologies of power - is increasing in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most executives have a simplistic idea of human behavior.
Emanating from the great engineering schools, their interpretation of psychology is mechanistic.
They adopt, through intellectual comfort, the old behavioral theory recently reactivated by the US "neuroscience" and unwittingly widely disseminated by research institutes and the media.
Thus, and by suggesting that it is possible to use the "levers" (sic) to engage employees, a recent Ipsos poll published in Le Figaro.fr encourages managers to adopt an attitude to a mechanistic management system that is unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure the mobilisation factors
