Oslo speech: 'Just war' earns Obama praise from right
The American right welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo on Friday and was pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the notion of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
Conservatives who mocked the award to Obama on October 9 applauded the president's speech this time, following the example of former vice presidential candidate Sarah Palin in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, Palin, the face of the right wing of the Republican Party, told USA Today, adding that she herself raised the issue of a "sometimes necessary" war in her just-published memoir.
War is, of course, the last thing I think the Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
"We have to stop the terrorists down there," she says.
Obama, who inherited two wars from his predecessor, George W. Bush, the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, sought Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision nine days ago to send 30,000 additional troops to Afghanistan.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done a "very good job" in Oslo.
I thought the speech was very good indeed, exulted the former President of the House of Representatives, who especially acknowledged the reference to "the existence of evil in the world" in the words of Obama.
In some parts of the country, the speech was seen as historic, said Ginrich, who was interviewed on the radio show "The Takeaway."
The former lawmaker, seen by some as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination in the 2012 presidential election, said he was pleased to see a "president of the left" who reminded Nobel committee members that they "are not free and cannot hand out a prize for peace if the use of force does not exist."
For Michael Gerson, a former writer for George W. Bush and now an editor at the Washington Post, Obama gave "a very American speech."
In addition to portraying himself as a "cosmopolitan," as "he always does," he spoke "like an American president," pointing out that Europeans "live in a security bubble that they didn't create and that they don't do much to protect," Gerson said.
Among the few unconvinced right-wingers, former U.N. Ambassador John Bolton, a Bush-era hawk, called the speech on the National Review Online website "dull, pompous, and uninspiring."
To the president's left, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich expressed concern about the way Barack Obama is defending the use of the armed forces.
If the war is waged under the guise of justice, he warns, the massacre of the innocent can easily be justified.
The center-left press, however, continues to praise the president.
The Los Angeles Times, which still believes the Nobel Prize was awarded prematurely to Obama, called the speech a "monumental work" even for a speaker like him known for his talent.
The speech in Oslo "provides a blueprint for guiding international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression," the Californian daily writes enthusiastically.
The New York Times believes that Obama "proclaimed the necessary discourse," calling his speech "somber and exemplary at the same time."
Truck drivers: Three marathons for a deal that secures Christmas supplies
After a three-week marathon of negotiations, the unions of the Road Workers Union and the TLF - the only employers "organisation remaining to the end - reached an agreement on Friday evening that puts an end to the strike order and the threat of severe supply shortages at Christmas.
At the signing session on Friday evening, Dominique Bussereau, State Secretary for Transport, "welcomed" the agreement, which was launched on Wednesday morning after several weeks of negotiations.
After a second night of negotiations, negotiators parted ways early Friday morning in hopes of quickly signing the agreement by late morning.
This was despite the fact that the three employers "associations (FNTR, Unostra and OTRE) had left the meeting outraged.
However, more than six hours went by from the start of the meeting at 11: 00 to the conclusion of the agreement, and it was not until 18: 00 that the agreement was signed.
The conflict "would have done a lot of damage to businesses" and "it was feared that it would affect the holidays at the end of the year," Bussereau said.
The agreement provides for a wage increase of 4% for the lowest wages (local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest wage groups (international transport).
The hourly rate for workers on the lowest wages will therefore rise from EUR 8.72 to EUR 9.06.
"It's not much, but we start small," said Patrice Clos (FO).
Activists are now instructed not to block the supply centers.
"However, there will probably always be some unruly people who are not happy with the agreement," he adds.
TLF chairman Philippe Grillot spoke of a "good agreement," although it was "difficult to concede these wage increases in the face of international competition."
According to him, the increase is 170 euros per month for the low wage groups and 100 to 120 euros for the high wage groups.
"This agreement is based on common sense and respect for workers," said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) spoke of "an historic agreement."
Richard Jaubert (CGT) said it was "an acceptable compromise."
The agreement also provides for a 3% increase in travel costs and the maintenance of the overall budget for road transport in the first half of 2010, which will make it possible, in particular, to address the issue of thirteenth-month salaries and the modernisation of collective agreements.
M. Bussereau recalled that "the reduction of taxes for employers amounting to 100 million euros" was the subject of an amendment by the government to the bill on corrected finances for 2009, which was passed by the National Assembly on Thursday night.
The government is demanding "an identical" vote from the Senate.
The signature of the TLF allows the agreement to apply first to the companies affiliated with this organisation and then, if extended by the Minister of Labour, to the entire profession.
This will be the case "in the shortest possible time," assures Bussereau.
Opposition from employers' associations can only delay the procedure.
The FNTR denounced a "fraudulent trade," because the €100 million "had already been promised to the sector to offset part of the carbon tax."
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate as quickly as possible, but not on the basis of a joint analysis, but in order not to annoy the goose-eaters on the approaching Christmas Day, laments Unostra.
For the Otre association, the agreement threatens to "dig a big grave for small and medium-sized enterprises in the sector over the next 12 months."
