Turkish constitutional court dissolves pro-Kurdish party. Decision with serious consequences
Turkey's Constitutional Court on Friday announced the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by angry demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision threatens to complicate enormously the work of the government, which is trying to reach out to the Kurdish community to put an end to 25 years of conflict.
The "Party for a Democratic Society" (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "site for activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," the president of the Constitutional Court, Hasim Kiliç, told the press four days after the decision.
According to Kiliç, the decision would have been taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority of seven votes needed to impose the dissolution, and he pointed out that 37 of the party's leaders, including chairman Ahmet Türk and parliamentarian Aysel Tugluk, were barred from politics for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Turk and Tugluk, as well as the confiscation of the party's assets.
The DTP now has 21 seats in parliament (out of 550).
Party leaders said before the verdict that MPs would rather leave parliament than sit like non-party MPs.
The decision followed a case initiated in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Turkish Federal Court, Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accused the DTP of following the "instructions" of the Kurdistan Workers "Party (PKK), which is considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and numerous other countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the PKK rebels "legal political showcase.
The party claims to have "no connection" with the PKK, but refuses to label it a terrorist organisation and calls on the government to negotiate.
The ruling by the Constitutional Court comes on the heels of the government's efforts to accommodate the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen the rights of the Kurds in order to drain Kurdish support for the PKK and put an end to the conflicts.
The leaders of the DTP affirm that a resolution could lead to a resumption of tensions in Southeast Anatolia, where numerous demonstrations against the detention conditions of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have led to clashes with police in recent weeks.
Since the court's announcement, thousands of demonstrators have gathered in front of the premises of the DTP in the metropolis of Diyarbakir in the southeast, which is predominantly populated by Kurds.
Police used tear gas grenades and water cannons as protesters began throwing Molotov cocktails and stones.
Hundreds of people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Türk said he expected the court's decision to "deepen the despair even further."
"Turkey cannot resolve this (Kurdish issue) by banning one party," he told the press.
The government, made up of a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
"We oppose the closure of the parties on principle.
That will not solve the problems, "said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
"This decision is a torpedo on the democratic opening promoted by the government," said political market observer Ahmet Insel.
"You can obviously expect a response from the PKK," he adds.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers in northern Turkey three days earlier, one of the most brutal attacks in recent months.
The onset of snow may come
A really crisp winter, that's what Wolfgang Brauburger wants.
Not because he wants to harass the citizens, says the winter service manager of the FES.
Rather, so that its employees can try out and master the entire vehicle technology.
It could be the first time this weekend, according to meteorologists.
More than 330 employees and 120 vehicles are ready to take care of snow and ice.
