That's why the FES starts at three o'clock in the morning, "so that the routes are free until rush hour."
It gets difficult when it snows only at 7.30am.
Then we have a problem, says the winter service manager, "because then nobody is prepared to make room for the gritters."
Only then, if it does not continue to snow, will it be the turn of feeder roads and access roads, including Rat-Beil-Straße.
Side streets and side streets are the last priority.
There will be complaints, Brauburger knows.
At five o'clock in the morning, the pedestrians of the FES set off, danger points and crossings are cleared as a matter of priority.
The FES can usually not take care of all bike paths.
There is a special service in Frankfurt, which mainly keeps an eye on the bridges from 10 p.m. to 4: 30 a.m., Brauburger says.
Since it is quickly slippery on these, as soon as the temperature drops below two degrees, the spreader is on its way.
He said police would also be called if necessary.
The Cradle of Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two meter long and 1.5 meter tall animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues report Thursday in the journal Science.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then located in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea at the equator.
Tawa opens a new window on the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It tells us a lot about the relationships, dispersal and characteristics of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We've sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, which is unprecedented for Triassic deposits, said team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some of the bones as new.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
Finding confirms theories about dinosaur prehistory
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, mostly only individual fragments can be found."
Other dinosaur experts don't necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly spectacular, but it does confirm some theories about the early history of the dinosaurs, says Martin Sander from the University of Bonn.
According to current doctrine, the dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the classification of these primordial dinosaurs is usually controversial.
For example, experts are debating when the lizards split into their three main lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor, and the birds, the four-legged sauropods and their relatives known as "long necks," and the herbivorous ornithischia, which included the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced features, says Nesbitt.
In the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of airbags, similar to those of the descendants of theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related lineage of the giant sauropods later also had airbags and lightweight bones, it is likely that the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three lines of development separated very early and spread from South America over all continents, which at that time still formed a single land mass as the supercontinent Pangaea.
This is supported by the fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not very closely related theropods.
The three cannot be descended from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn-based paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, a distorted picture could arise, because in South America there are simply a lot of primitive dino fossils preserved, while on other continents hardly anything is to be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant agricultural vertebrates of the Middle Ages is still a mystery.
During the Triassic, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and pterosaurs, and numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while the relationship at the border of the Triassic and Jurassic became extinct.
Success story didn't last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this shift, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted to beat the competition from the field.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped a group of animals to blossom, which had also developed in the Triassic and had been living in the shadows ever since: mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and the signatories are international.
