New Silicon Valley
For many years it was considered a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenograd, one of ten districts of the capital Moscow, was a heavily guarded site for secret armaments research in the Soviet Union.
Today, the commune with its 216,000 inhabitants, 37 kilometres from the centre of Moscow, is regarded as "Russian Silicon Valley."
Important research and production facilities for micro- and nanoelectronics are located here.
Since September 2008, representatives of Selenograd had already established contacts with the Frankfurt science centre Riedberg - with the university institutes and the companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were several reciprocal visits, and on Wednesday Selenograd and Riedberg signed a "Protocol on Closer Cooperation" in Frankfurt.
Deputy Mayor of Moscow Yuri Roslyak and Prefect Anatoly Smirnov of Selenograd led the Russian delegation, while Planning Minister Edwin Schwarz signed for Frankfurt.
In 2010, representatives of the FIZ and small and medium-sized enterprises of the scientific research focus will travel to Selenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
It is a question of continuous scientific exchange.
But it is also about economic relations.
FIZ companies will be able to gain a foothold in the growing Russian market.
Conversely, Russian science companies want to win contracts in Germany.
Selenograd is the seat of important Russian research institutes and companies.
These include the Moscow Institute of Electronic Engineering, the large corporations Sitronics and Rossiyskaya Elektronika.
The Commune was founded in 1958 as a so-called "socialist planned city" for armaments research.
Selenograd (literally translated "Grünstadt") got its name from the wooded hills in which the research facilities are embedded.
Stuttgart brake pad
The dimension of Stuttgart 21 cannot be overstated.
For the supporters of the project, it is simply about "the new heart of Europe."
Quite so. S21 is much more than the lowering of a railway station, more than a monstrous construction project that will plunge the city of the Baden-Württemberg capital into utter construction chaos for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 was born out of the spirit of the 1980s.
Terminals with tracks that end in the middle of the city were considered transport fossils of the 19th century, which acted as brake blocks of modern rail transport, because it once took an enormous amount of time to rearrange locomotives from the back to the front.
Drive in, keep short, keep driving - that's how it should be.
And that's why the terminals should disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart: a transit station, which is located about half way along the trans-European rail highway between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava - hence the slogan "Heart of Europe."
S21 is indeed being tackled now, even though the visions of the 1980s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even very ambitious planners have recognized that it is almost priceless in the Hessian and Bavarian cities to implement lowering.
Terminals, however, no longer have an entry and exit problem, since there are modern turning trains with locomotives and control cars at both ends.
Nevertheless: Stuttgart 21 along with the new ICE line to Ulm is now being tackled.
State and local politicians have pushed it through.
Rail participates, also because the risks of the largest infrastructure project in the Republic are borne by taxpayers and not by state corporations.
The project can still be reasonably justified in terms of urban planning.
New urban space is being created, which - if the computer-generated graphics of the planners are to be believed - will be furnished with plenty of greenery.
S21 is harmful to the rail transport system.
The transit station and the extension of the line are intended for passenger traffic, which - typically in the 80s - was credited with huge growth.
Back then, there was no competition from low-cost airlines.
Modern transport policy must, however, first and foremost focus on strengthening freight transport, as rail transport is considerably more environmentally friendly than road transport.
But the new line is not suitable for freight trains because of steep gradients.
Even more serious is the fact that S21 indirectly affects many other rail projects.
A good six billion euros are to be bundled up in Swabian.
That is the official figure.
Experts believe that ten to 15 billion is realistic.
What is certain is that the next decade will see a lack of money at other intersections and bottlenecks in the network.
A total of sixty major projects are on the list of the Ministry of Transport.
One of the most important is the extension of the 180-kilometre-long route through the Rhine valley.
Construction on the line has been slow-motion since 1987.
It would be urgently necessary to press the tube correctly here.
But S21 will act as a brake pad.
