Dreamworlds
Some see images when awake and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
The boundaries between imagination and reality are not only blurred in the case of the mentally ill and in drug intoxication.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we are free to indulge in the wildest imaginations and fantasies.
Whoever experiences dream-like states while awake, sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is generally regarded in the modern Western world as crazy or addicted to drugs, or at least as an eccentric.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the case of the mentally ill or in drug intoxication.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that enable us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels sometimes blur the boundaries between dream, delusion, and reality.
Dreamlike altered states of wakefulness can occur in many different forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusion.
Although triggers and effects may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic raptures, psychosis and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of the brain's neuronal messengers - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin, and acetylcholine - is derailed and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts are very common during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity no longer has power over him
The connection between delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since antiquity.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of dream in an awake state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great similarity of insanity with dream states," and for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis, with all its inconsistencies, delusions, and delusions of the senses."
It is autumn 2001, when Henning T. turns into a cartoon character.
His body is two-dimensional and squeaky-colored.
Gravity no longer has any power over him, he floats on the ceiling.
He senses a kick.
Behind him winged devil figures with blood-red, distorted grimaces, gnashing their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Loud, vicious voices roar from walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. rips two cables out of the stereo, ties them into a loop and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
He gets on a loudspeaker and puts the noose around his neck.
Jumps.
The noose loosens.
This is supposed to be a lesson for you, the voices scream in an eardrum-shattering chorus, "Go to the clinic and be healed!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychosis, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective-paranoid psychosis, moreover, he is manic-depressive, he takes medication for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
"During my psychosis, I experienced the worst fear and the deepest despair," he says.
The Mirages are Cruel Reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and psychiatric hospitals treat it as the second most common condition after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers are usually no longer able to distinguish between the inner and outer world, they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationships or persecution.
Particularly common is the hearing of voices - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The affected person can no longer separate the important from the unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like dreams, psychosis opens the floodgates to a flood of ideas and fantasies that come from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subjective, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the centre of the action, everything has a meaning directed towards him.
At the same time, he finds himself in a passive role, as in a dream, overwhelmed by what is happening and unable to actively shape it.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
A reality check is usually not possible for them, the illusions are cruel reality, awakening excluded.
To have experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in dreams, Fuchs says, "the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, is fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of experience takes place within the real framework.
Exactly why our brains strike such a chord is still a mystery to researchers.
Emergency situations can cause any person to temporarily lose touch with reality, Fuchs says.
But not everyone will develop psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers believe there is minimal brain damage in sufferers.
We suspect that the neural maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, for example by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains a mystery how the disturbance of the neural system comes about, which moreover does not manifest itself at all at first for many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also cause psychosis as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brain is running hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others spend money on drugs to get them, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether miraculous images are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and illusory phenomena for ten years, and last year he analyzed his findings in the book "The Unreal World in Our Mind."
Hallucinations are one of the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of an astonishing number of other illnesses.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's and brain trauma.
Surprisingly, even healthy people's brains hallucinate under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, Kasten said, are made up of memory contents that are normally retained.
They arise when areas of the brain where sensory perception is processed are overactive or inhibited too little; when our brain is running hot or when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can cause this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also attraction, stress, lovesickness or other mental states of emergency.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents said they had experienced hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old. She lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends grammar school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it were not for the images and voices.
During the break it can happen that a lanky boy with long, dark hair responds to it.
When he replies, his classmates look at him in surprise - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They consider the shy girl to be a spun daydreamer, but Sarah K. does not dream, she knows that.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bench next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for a moment.
It's a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she wonders sometimes.
But she knows that this boy and the other mirages are not real and will disappear again.
At night the apparitions are mostly scary
Often the illusions are also a burden.
When she is sitting in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the subject matter, because the teacher is introducing a new classmate to her eyes and ears, while he is explaining mathematical equations audibly and visibly to everyone else on the blackboard.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which comes far too rarely and far too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees, the grimaces or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, are created in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she shouts at the creatures.
She doesn't tell parents or friends about it, they think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated from high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
The hallucinations stopped a year ago.
Ever since she contacted the psychologist on the internet, she knows full well that she's not crazy.
Delusion is also a work of art out of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from stimuli, they are most likely to have hallucinations after a while, Kasten says.
I suspect the brain is then underemployed and provides its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she calls Dad has not been her biological father for as long as she can remember.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations involve the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and sounds, sufferers such as Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between illusions and reality. "Every experience," Kasten says, "takes place in the brain, where reality is depicted.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain creates, which is why they seem so real. "
Kasten also regards nocturnal dream images as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy are able to recognize their illusions as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to also value hallucinations as a special ability.
Border state between dream and hallucination
In our too consciousness-centered world, imaginary experience is unfortunately most often pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, distressing illness, but it also contains positive, creative things - delusion is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of dream-like altered wakefulness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the experienced person considers to be real and which he cannot distinguish retrospectively from the waking state.
The oneiroid state of consciousness arises in traumatic or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis when fully conscious.
When a person is threatened by loss of self and world, for example by persistent, complete immobility, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline state between dream and hallucination.
Since coping with a situation in reality is not possible, a change of world takes place, but the real situation is made present in the imagination.
An intensive form of generating meaning and making sense in an intrinsically unbearable situation, which enables us humans to create our own ability not to sink into a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" as a rescue operation for the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, while his body is condemned to mobility in intensive care.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden old man, on board a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
In the early Middle Ages, he lived among nobles who manufactured drugs from blood.
Abducted by a Greek on a motorcycle in his home country, surfing in the firn snow of the Alps with his hospital bed and meeting a Korean mafioso.
It is completely absorbed in the imagined event, everything is real, even later in the memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is another condition, he describes his experience.
In complete contrast, the memories from mental journeys are still clear to me after years and in incidental details.
More clearly and more intensely even than what was really experienced.
The intensity of this experience bursts the horizon of our other worldly experiences, says the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroids, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug intoxication show how fragile our inner images of outer reality are even when awake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
