The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market limited due to motherhood.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and, if so, what kind of job they do.
Those who do not do any other work outside the home, work part-time or have no fixed contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
By contrast, women with permanent jobs, especially in the public sector, postpone starting a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the 35-49 age group with a permanent job do not have their first child on average until 3.7 years after they have moved in, a figure that rises to 4.1 years for women with a permanent job who have taken longer to achieve this and who have only realised their contraction and first child much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a great influence on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar in terms of conception readiness, "explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account when women get married and have their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference could also be observed in women of the same age.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, women became first-time mothers at 25.1 and 32.1, on average, depending on whether they only completed lower secondary school or higher education.
Furthermore, there is another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
Whereas women with a high school diploma get married before their first permanent job and have their first child, women with a middle or high school diploma do it the other way around, first looking for a permanent job and then getting married and then having their first child, notes Delgado.
