Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system at the time, and as is currently the case with the ESP stability control system, emergency braking systems must become compulsory in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, with a waiting period until the end of February 2011 for the remaining vehicles.
The aim of the measure adopted by the European Union is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems, due to their functioning, can also help to prevent many rear-end collisions.
The role of the emergency brake assist is to apply more pressure to the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects on the brake pedal based on the braking force applied by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure to the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even manage to press the brake pedal before the collision, and half of them had not braked fully.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system, thereby reducing the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during braking.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related fatal accidents could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents involving personal injury is expected to be prevented - once so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
The vehicle is then equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, applying a slight pressure on the brakes at the same time.
When the driver responds, the system helps him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning, and even if the collision is already inevitable, the Brake Assist exerts maximum pressure on the brakes to minimize the damage.
