Behind the wheel of the Porsche Boxster Spyder
For the development of their latest and very expensive jewel, the engineers used the Boxster S as the basis, but managed to make it 80 kilograms lighter, bringing it down to just 1,275 kilograms.
In order to achieve this, the first thing they did was to do without the automatic hinged roof, which was replaced by a canvas roof with manual drive, which alone saved 21 kilos; thanks to the aluminium doors used in this model, such as those of the GT3, another 15 "disappeared"; with the removal of the air conditioning, another 13; in addition, the fuel tank was reduced from 64 to 54 litres, saving a further 7 kilos; with the installation of sporty Bacquet seats, another 12 and with the light 19-inch rims, another five were saved.
Then, by dispensing with the CDR-30 audio system, they had lost another six kilos, and by replacing the door handles with fabric handles, they had achieved the missing kilo.
Although it is also available with the PDK dual-clutch gearbox, the test drive was done with a 6-speed manual gearbox, mainly on the smaller California highways, on mountain stretches that were really very winding.
With his driving you can only give him the mark impeccable.
However, the reduction in his weight has not in any way resulted in him not being so safe on the road any more.
In fact, the opposite is the case: we haven't tried such a small and light model for a long time, but at the same time it gives you a feeling of great safety when cornering, even at high speed.
He is a small athlete, able to warm his muscles in a low gear in the required time, until we give him the orders to speed, brake, recover and then get everything out of his engine again...
He does everything we tell him, the car does everything we tell him with our hands on the steering wheel, thanks to its steering, which is as communicative as it is precise.
And he does it with the precision of a surgeon.
An engine sound for all tastes
The sound of its 320 bhp V6 boxer (10 more than the Boxster S) is extremely successful and can be enhanced with the 'sport' option and a system that can change the engine noise, which was already used for the first time on the Panamera.
The acceleration is unimaginably brutal, whether from standing up or speeding up again.
Suspension is strong, but not hard or uncomfortable.
The asphalt on the country roads where we drove the Boxster Spyder was already quite damaged, but the car coped well with the potholes.
The electronic assistants had almost nothing to do on the whole track, even though we found ice at dawn on some of these corners and a bit of grit in the morning.
In summary, it is an ultralight car, a car with which you can have an indescribable driving pleasure, as it is usually rather rare, and there is much more to it than just a small improvement on the Boxster S.
The car will be on the market in February 2010 and will cost 70,831 EURO.
