How much should you earn based on your Facebook profile?
Facebook users can now find out the salary they should earn based on their profile thanks to the new Trovit application, the search engine with the highest number of ads for real estate, jobs and cars in Spain.
The tool "How much should you earn?" calculates the salaries of users based on more than 140,000 job openings available at Trovit in Spain. Users have access to a form on Facebook where they can enter their occupation, work experience, age and the city in which they work.
Just one week after the application became available for the first time, the search engine found that the average Spanish worker "feels poorly paid," explains Albert Ribera, who is responsible for the Trovit product, in a press release.
The Spaniards are the lowest paid according to the data Trovit has through its search engines in the UK and France.
A British programmer gets an annual gross salary of 45,226 euros and a Frenchman 31,059 euros, as opposed to the 24,000 euros earned by a Spaniard.
As a result, a lorry driver has a net annual salary of €34,247 in England, €25,751 in France and €16,420 in Spain.
According to Trovit, the lowest paid job in Spain is that of a waiter with 11,592 euros net a year, followed by that of a salesman with 14,725 euros and that of a worker with 15,667 euros.
The most searched posts on the internet in the last three months are those of a driver, part-time workers and social workers.
