Acciona competes with Hochtief and Bouygues for its first motorway in Australia
Acciona is fighting for approval of its first motorway in Australia, a market in which it already operates as an energy and water company.
The construction in question is a tunnel that will cost 1.7 billion Australian dollars (approximately 1.047 billion euros).
The French company Bouygues and Germany's Hochtief are its competitors.
A 5 kilometre tunnel in the Australian city of Brisbane, on the east coast, has become the best opportunity for Acciona to establish itself as a construction company and motorway operator in the country.
The municipality wants the construction to be completed by the end of 2014.
After opting for a public-private partnership (PPP is the English abbreviation) to move the project forward on the basis of a business plan drawn up by Ernst & Young, the administration already has a final list of candidates for construction and tollbooth management.
In anticipation of the offers presented in May, the estimated investment amounts to 1.7 billion Australian dollars (1.047 billion euros), with three consortia, mainly made up of European construction companies, competing in the final phase.
The group, called Transcity, is led by Acciona, the only Spanish company, and its partners are BMD and Ghella.
The first is one of the largest construction companies in Australia, while the second, based in Italy, is one of the best specialists in civil engineering.
Acciona's team will be pitted against the Northern Direct consortium composed of the British company Laing O'Rourke, Australia's Transfield, which is responsible for infrastructure, and the French construction group Bouygues.
The third and final shortlisted consortium is LBRJV, made up of the capital of Australia's Leighton (a subsidiary of the German construction company Hochtief, which in turn is part of ACS), the local Baulderstone (owned by the German group Bilfinger Berger) and the French company Razel, which specialises in public works.
The Australian infrastructure market promises huge construction and privatisation, but has a hurdle to overcome, as access can only be gained through the purchase of a local developer.
A strategy that the aforementioned companies Hochtief or Bilfinger, in addition to Asian references, have followed, and which the Spanish construction giants have yet to pursue.
Even ACS only entered this market through its 30% stake in Hochtief, owner of the aforementioned Leighton.
Millions in assets
Acciona relies on this geographical area of the utmost importance for the industry, where it is already well known for its activities as an energy supplier and in the desalination industry.
Among other assets, it already has its largest windmill park (192 MW) in Victoria and leads the group of companies contracted to build and manage Adelaide's desalination plant with a budget of $700 million.
His intention now is to consolidate in these two areas and to exploit these synergies to gain access to the construction and infrastructure sectors.
The underground toll road, promoted by the Brisbane City Infrastructure Authority and called the Northern Link, will link the western motorway at Toowong with the Kelvin Grove bypass (see map) for 5 kilometres through tunnels, the largest congestion reduction measure on Brisbane's roads.
The timetable issued by the municipality foresees the award of the contract for summer 2010 and the start of construction work in December next year.
Although this toll road is already scheduled to open to traffic in the final months of 2014, it is expected that construction will continue until 2016.
The tunnel was designed in 2005.
It has two lanes in each direction, an electronic toll collection system and a complex ventilation system.
The Queensland government is contributing 500 million Australian dollars (308 million euros) to the funding.
For Hochtief, Brisbane is big business.
Australia continues to award sizeable contracts to Hochtief, which yesterday signed a $154 million contract with the government.
ACS, through its domestic subsidiary Leighton, will improve the infrastructure of the domestic fibre-optic broadband network.
This improvement will provide high-speed internet access for 400,000 people and will keep the German company busy for 18 months.
On the other hand, the company has received the 27-storey King George Tower project in the Australian city of Brisbane. Construction has not yet begun and Hochtief has received 129 million euros for it.
In the United Kingdom, in Manchester, it is also competing with Laing O'Rourke for the construction and management of two schools over a period of 25 years.
The initial investment amounts to EUR 75 million.
